Easy Cherry Almond Scones 🍒 Mother’s Day is just a few days away! May I suggest treating the moms in your life to a hot cup of coffee and these absolutely delicious homemade scones to start the day? (And if you are a mom, just go ahead and send this post to the people who are going to make the day special for you, they’ll get the hint. 😉)

Scones are one of my favorite things to bake. You only need one bowl and about 30 minutes start to finish, they only require a few simple ingredients, and they’re totally adaptable to whatever you have in your fridge or pantry. This combination of cherries and almonds is one of my faves.

Ingredients
2 cups all purpose flour
1/4 cup white sugar
2 tsp baking powder
1/2 tsp kosher salt
4 tbsp cold unsalted butter
1 cup fresh or frozen cherries, pitted and halved
1/2 cup sliced almonds, plus more for topping
3/4 cup heavy cream, plus more for brushing
1/2 tsp vanilla extract
Turbinado sugar for dusting

Directions
Preheat oven to 425. Whisk flour, sugar, baking powder, and salt together in a large bowl. Cut in the butter, then add cherries and almonds. Mix cream and vanilla together then pour into the bowl with the rest of the ingredients. Stir with a fork until combined, then turn onto a floured work surface and use your hands to shape dough into a disc. Cut into 6 even triangles and place on a parchment lined baking sheet. Brush with a bit more cream, dust with some turbinado sugar, and top with a few sliced almonds. Bake for about 20 minutes or until golden brown.

Let’s hear it for snack plate dinners! 🥕🍅🥩🫒🧀 We’re only just approaching summer and I already don’t want to turn on the stove or oven to cook. Luckily the whole family loves a “snack plate” dinner. Bonus is it often ends up more nutritious, easier, and faster than cooking! And the kids feel like they’re getting away with “snacks” for dinner so they’re delighted.

On this board: leftover grilled filet mignon sliced thinly and sprinkled with @maldonsalt flakes, homemade sun-dried tomato sourdough, horseradish cream sauce (I just mix together some crème fraîche or sour cream, grated horseradish, salt, and pepper), tricolored carrots, castelvetrano olives, spicy blue cheese, baby radishes, Marcona almonds with rosemary, heirloom tomatoes, sugar snap peas, hummus topped with olive oil and homemade Aleppo pepper flakes, cornishons, aged Gouda, and pistachios.

Frozen Yogurt Bark 🍒 A refreshing and healthy snack that’s perfect for your Memorial Day cookouts this weekend!

Ingredients
2 cups plain yogurt
2 tbsp honey
1/2 tsp vanilla extract
1/2 cup cherries, halved and pitted
1/2 cup blueberries
1/2 cup @ghirardelli white chocolate chips

Directions
Combine yogurt, honey, and vanilla and mix together. Spread on a parchment lined quarter sheet pan and arrange fruit and chocolate chips on top. Freeze for at least 5 hours, preferably overnight.

Basil Pesto 🌱 Nothing says summer like classic basil pesto. I make this a few times every season with fresh basil from our garden and it never lasts for long in the fridge. We use it in pasta, on grilled chicken, in a panini, with tomatoes and mozzarella, and sometimes just with some crackers and a glass of wine.

Ingredients
4 cups packed fresh basil leaves, washed and dried well
2/3 cup toasted pine nuts
5 cloves garlic, chopped
1 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
1/2 tsp salt
1/4 tsp pepper
3/4 cup extra virgin olive oil

Directions
Combine basil and pine nuts in a food processor and pulse until blended together. Add garlic and pulse, then add cheese, salt, and pepper. Pulse again until well combined, then turn it on all the way and slowly stream in the olive oil until emulsified. Add additional salt and pepper to taste. Makes about 2 cups of pesto.

Burst Cherry Tomatoes with Burrata and Basil 🍅 The warmer weather has me craving big, juicy heirloom tomatoes for caprese salad, but we still have to wait a bit for those to be in season here in Northern Virginia. The good news is you can get delicious little cherry tomatoes year round! And sautéing them for a bit turns them into perfectly sweet, slightly tart, jammy little bites that honestly taste better than candy. Tear some burrata on top and serve with fresh arugula and thick slices of toasted sourdough for the perfect early summer snack.

Ingredients
1 tbsp olive oil
2 pints cherry tomatoes
4 cloves garlic, minced
1/4 cup fresh basil, chopped
Hot pepper flakes to taste
Kosher salt and black pepper to taste
2 balls of burrata (or mozzarella)
Sourdough bread, sliced and toasted

Heat olive oil in a skillet over medium heat and cook cherry tomatoes until bursted. Add garlic and sauté for another minute. Add basil, hot pepper flakes, salt, and pepper and continue cooking for another few minutes. Let cool a bit. Tear burrata into pieces and arrange on top of the tomatoes. Serve with some fresh, peppery arugula and lots of warm crusty sourdough bread for scooping up every last bite.

Berries and cream sourdough galette 🫐🍓 This combination of fresh sweet berries and creamy vanilla mascarpone is perfection, and the sourdough discard pie dough recipe is one of my greatest inventions. It’s a cross between buttery pie crust and flaky puff pastry and it’s perfect for galettes. But if you don’t have sourdough starter you can substitute regular pie dough and this recipe will still work beautifully!

Ingredients for dough:
3/4 cup AP flour
1/2 tsp sugar
1/2 tsp kosher salt
1/2 cup butter
1/2 cup unfed cold sourdough starter

Ingredients for galette:
3 cups mixed berries - I use a combination of strawberries, raspberries, blueberries, and blackberries
Juice from half a lemon
1 tbsp sugar
1 tbsp flour
4 oz mascarpone
1 tsp vanilla
1/4 cup sugar 
Pinch salt 
1 egg, beaten
Turbinado sugar

Directions
Mix together flour, salt, and sugar in a food processor. Add cubes of butter and pulse until combined (you still want to see pea-sized pieces of butter in there). Scoop the sourdough starter on top (make sure it’s straight from the fridge) and pulse until the dough begins to come together. Form dough into a disc and refrigerate for about an hour.

Preheat the oven to 400°. Roll out the dough and place on a parchment-lined baking sheet. Mix berries, lemon juice, sugar, and flour in a bowl and set aside. In a separate bowl, combine mascarpone, vanilla, sugar, and salt and mix well until smooth. Spread mascarpone mixture on the pie dough, leaving a couple inches around the edge. Pile the berries on top (do not add the accumulated liquid). Fold the dough up around the filling, brush with egg, and sprinkle with Turbinado sugar. Bake for 30-40 min until golden brown.

Directions
Throw the chicken, hot sauce, and butter in the slow cooker for 4 hours on high, then shred with a fork.

Note: All of these inclusions ideas are with my classic sourdough recipe and process in mind (find it on my feed or in the comments here).

🍒 Dried fruit and nut sourdough:
(Here I’m making cherry walnut, I also love raisin pecan, fig walnut, and cranberry pecan)

Wrapping up @30minutefoodie Sourdough School Phase 3 with a few of my top scoring tips:

1 - Cold dough is easier to score, score straight from the fridge if you do an overnight proof

3 - Dust with all purpose flour to provide a beautiful contrast in your scoring design

5 - The deeper you cut, the more the bread with spread as it cooks, use light delicate cuts for more intricate designs

Sriracha honey salmon and sushi rice bowl 🐟🍚 If you’re new here, this is one of my most popular recipes! I share it every few months because it’s easily one of our top 3 favorite dinners, and I know a lot of you love it too. The salmon is so easy to cook (you can’t mess it up) and the glaze is the perfect combo of savory, sweet, and spicy. Serve the salmon over the most delicious sushi rice, add some avocado, cucumber, and edamame, then top with green onion and sesame seeds... it’s perfect.

Ingredients for marinade
1/2 cup soy sauce
2 tbsp rice vinegar
2 tbsp sriracha
2 tbsp honey
1 tbsp minced garlic
1 tbsp minced ginger

Ingredients for rice bowl
2-3 salmon filets
Marinade
2 tbsp vegetable oil
2 cups short grain rice
1/4 cup rice vinegar
1 tbsp white sugar
1 tsp kosher salt
Avocado
Green onion
Edamame
Cucumber
Sesame seeds

Combine marinade ingredients, mix well, and pour over salmon in a large resealable bag. Marinade in the fridge for at least 2 hours, or up to 12.

Heat oil in a nonstick pot over medium high (make sure it has a lid!). Sear salmon skin-side up for 2-3 minutes, then flip and cook for another 2 minutes. Pour the marinade over the fish, turn the heat down to low, cover, and simmer for 30 minutes. Remove the salmon and let it rest, then turn up the heat to medium high and let the sauce thicken and reduce by about a third. 

In the meantime, cook the rice. Mix together rice vinegar, sugar, and salt (you may need to heat it a bit to get everything to dissolve). Pour mixture over cooked rice and mix gently. Cover with a towel until ready to use.

Serve the salmon over sushi rice, spoon glaze on top, and garnish with cucumber, edamame, sliced scallions, avocado, and sesame seeds.

Basil Pesto recipe:
Ingredients
4 cups packed fresh basil leaves, washed and dried well
2/3 cup toasted pine nuts
5 cloves garlic, chopped
1 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
1/2 tsp salt
1/4 tsp pepper
3/4 cup extra virgin olive oil
Directions
Combine basil and pine nuts in a food processor and pulse until blended together. Add garlic and pulse, then add cheese, salt, and pepper. Pulse again until well combined, then turn it on all the way and slowly stream in the olive oil until emulsified. Add additional salt and pepper to taste. Makes about 2 cups of pesto.

Easy Ratatouille 🍅 Not only is this one of the prettiest dishes ever and a great way to use all your beautiful seasonal veggies, but it’s also a hit with adults and kids alike. We love this as a side with some grilled chicken, or sometimes we add ground beef or turkey to the sauce to amp up the protein for an easy and healthy one-dish dinner.

Ingredients
4 tbsp olive oil, divided
1 shallot, chopped
2 cloves garlic, minced
1 tbsp Calabrian chili sauce (optional)
1 jar marinara sauce or can of crushed tomatoes
3-4 cups baby spinach
1 large or 2 medium zucchini
1 large or 2 medium yellow squash
5-6 medium tomatoes
Salt and pepper
¼ cup parmesan cheese

Note: this preparation works better when your zucchini, squash, and tomatoes are about the same diameter.

Directions
Preheat oven to 375°. Warm a couple tablespoons of olive oil in a pan and sauté shallot until softened, about 5 min. Add garlic and bomba sauce (if using) and cook for another couple of minutes. Mix in jar of sauce and bring to a boil. Add spinach and cook until wilted. Add salt and pepper to taste, then turn down and simmer for a few minutes to let the flavors come together. Remove from heat and pour into a baking dish.

Slice zucchini, squash, and tomato thinly and stack them together, alternating in a regular pattern. Arrange veggies in the baking dish on their side all the way around the side, then in the middle. Drizzle with remaining olive oil and some salt and pepper, then throw it in the oven covered with foil for 40 minutes. Remove foil and continue cooking until veggies are soft, about another 30 minutes. Finish with another drizzle of olive oil and a sprinkle of grated parmesan cheese.

Classic crab cakes 🦀 These have tons of flavor without overshadowing the delicate and delicious lump crab. Serve with some fresh veggies and an ice cold beer and you have the perfect dinner for a warm summer night.

1 large egg

3 tsp dijon mustard
2 tsp Worcestershire sauce

A couple dashes of hot sauce
1 tbsp chopped fresh parsley
1/4 tsp kosher salt
1 pound fresh lump crab meat

Ingredients
2 tbsp butter
1 small sweet onion, sliced
2 garlic cloves, minced
1/2 pound cooked chorizo, sliced or crumbled
2 cups baby spinach
12 large eggs
1/4 cup heavy cream
4 oz @celebrity_goat cheese
Salt and pepper to taste

Sauté onions in butter until softened, add garlic and cook for a couple minutes. Add the chorizo and let it get nice and hot and crispy, then add the spinach. In the meantime, crack the eggs into a bowl and whisk in the cream, add salt and pepper to taste. Pile spinach mixture into an oven safe dish and pour eggs on top. Break goat cheese into chunks and arrange around the top. Bake at 350° for 35-40 min.

Pumpkin baked Brie en croûte with pumpkin butter and maple pecans 🍂 This is such a fun and festive appetizer for fall, and it’s so easy to put together! Serve straight from the oven with a baguette and apple slices and you have a guaranteed crowd pleaser 🙌

Ingredients
1 sheet puff pastry, thawed
3 tbsp pumpkin butter
3 tbsp pecans, chopped
1 round brie cheese
Egg, beaten
Flake salt
1 bell pepper stem

Directions
Preheat oven to 400°. Lay out puff pastry and spread pumpkin butter in the middle, taking up the same area as the round of Brie. Arrange chopped pecans and Brie on top and fold the pastry around everything, cutting off excess if necessary. Use 4 pieces of kitchen twine to tie around the pastry, this will create the pumpkin shape. Brush with beaten egg, top with flake salt, and bake for 20-25 min or until golden brown. Cut the twine off your “pumpkin” and use a toothpick to attach the pepper stem.

Simple Peach Crisp 🍑 This dessert (or breakfast?? 😉) couldn’t be easier or more delicious. It comes together in just a few minutes and is one of my favorite ways to highlight perfect end-of-summer peaches.

Ingredients for filling
4 cups sliced peaches
Juice from half a lemon 
2 tbsp cornstarch 
1/4 cup sugar 
1/2 tsp cinnamon
Tiny pinch of salt

Ingredients for topping
1 cup rolled oats
3/4 cup flour
3/4 cup brown sugar
1/2 tsp baking powder
3/4 tsp cinnamon 
Pinch of kosher salt
6 tbsp melted butter

Directions
Preheat oven to 350. Combine filling ingredients in a bowl, stir well, and set aside. In a separate bowl, stir together the topping ingredients, making sure to mix in the melted butter last. Pile peaches in a baking dish (I use a pie plate) and crumble the oat mixture on top. Bake for about 45 min or until the peach sauce is bubbling and appears thick around the edge - it’s important to wait for this to happen or the filling will be runnier and the flavor isn’t as condensed and jammy! Let the crisp cool for a few minutes to let the sauce continue to thicken before digging in.

Fig and Vanilla Jam 💜

Fresh figs are only in season for a very short time, so I always love to make a batch of fig jam to last all year long! It’s perfect for spreading on toast or scones, adding to a turkey sandwich (this is especially yummy with leftovers the day after Thanksgiving!), making a fig, prosciutto, and arugula flatbread pizza, or even just throwing on a cheese and charcuterie board. The beautiful jars also make great gifts for the upcoming holiday season!

Ingredients 
2 pounds of fresh figs, stemmed and cut into 1/4 inch pieces (about 4 cups)
1½ cups granulated sugar
¼ cup water
¼ cup strained lemon juice
Pinch of kosher salt
1 vanilla bean, split and seeded

Directions
Add all ingredients to a large saucepan and bring to a boil. Once the sugar dissolves, reduce the heat to low and simmer uncovered for about an hour, checking and stirring every 10 minutes or so. Once the jam is thick remove the vanilla bean. Carefully spoon jam into sterile jars, leaving ¼ inch space, and close with a sterile lid. Gently place jars in a large pot of boiling water and process covered for 15 minutes. Remove the jars and let cool on the counter. Store jam at room temperature for up to 18 months. Makes 24 oz of jam.

Blueberry and Peach Cake 🫐🍑 I can’t let summer come to a close without making this - it’s sunshine on a plate.

Ingredients for cake
8 tbsp salted butter, room temp
1/2 cup sugar
1/2 cup greek yogurt
Zest from 1 lemon
2 tsp vanilla extract
3 large eggs, room temp
1 1/2 cups flour
1 1/2 tsp baking powder
1/2 tsp kosher salt
1 1/2 cups fresh blueberries
4 tablespoons peach preserves
1 tbsp turbinado sugar

Ingredients for glaze
2 tbsp lemon juice
3/4 cup powdered sugar

Directions
Preheat oven to 375. Cream together butter and sugar in a stand mixer, then add yogurt, lemon zest, and vanilla and continue mixing. Add eggs one at a time and mix until smooth and incorporated. Sift together dry ingredients and slowly add to the mixer. Remove the bowl and fold in the blueberries, leaving out about 1/4 cup for the top of the cake. Add half of the batter to a greased loaf pan, then swirl in 2 tbsp of peach preserves. Add the remaining batter and swirl in the remaining peach preserves on top, followed by the rest of the blueberries and turbinado sugar. Bake for about an hour until done. Cool completely before removing from the pan. Whisk together the lemon juice and powdered sugar and pour the glaze over the top of the cake.

One of my most popular recipes - hot pepper jelly! 🌶 

This spicy/sweet combo is so incredibly delicious. Pile it on cream cheese and serve with sea salt crackers, buttermilk biscuits, or savory shortbread. Add it to a cheese board to give a little kick to plain goat cheese or Manchego. Use it as a glaze for salmon or pork. Serve at Thanksgiving with hunks of hot, buttery cornbread. Add it to a turkey and Swiss panini. Grab your slow cooker and make an appetizer with a dollop of jelly and some frozen mini meatballs. The possibilities are endless.

TIP: Preserve the jelly in pretty jars and you have the perfect hostess/holiday gift for the approaching season!

Ingredients
12 jalapeño peppers (I use mostly red jalapeños to give the jelly a brighter color)
2 red bell peppers
5 1/2 cups of granulated sugar
1 1/2 cups white vinegar
1/2 teaspoon salt
3 ounces liquid pectin

Directions
Rough chop all the peppers (leave some seeds and veins in the jalapeños if you like a little more heat, and wear gloves to chop them!). Throw all peppers in a food processor and pulse until finely chopped. Strain through a mesh strainer to drain excess liquid. Don’t skip this step or your jelly won’t set right.

Combine the chopped peppers, sugar, vinegar, and salt in a large stock pot and bring to a boil. Boil for 10 minutes, stirring to prevent it from boiling over. Add the pectin and boil for another minute, then remove from heat.

Carefully ladle hot jelly into warm sterile jars, leaving 1/4 inch headspace. Top with lids and then seal jars in boiling water for 10 minutes. Let the jelly rest on the counter for 1 day to fully set, then you can store it on the shelf for up to a year. If you want to skip this step you can just store the jelly in the fridge for up to 2 months. This recipe makes about 60oz of jelly.

My classic sourdough recipe:

Ingredients
100g active starter
375g filtered 75° water, divided
50g whole wheat flour
200g bread flour
250g all-purpose flour
10g kosher salt

Directions
Combine starter and 350g water in a large glass bowl and stir to dissolve. Mix in flour. Cover and let sit for 40 minutes.

Add salt and remaining 25g water and knead in, pinching and squeezing the dough until the salt is dissolved and water is absorbed. Cover and let sit for 30 minutes.

Stretch the dough gently and fold over itself, rotate 90° and repeat until you’ve done all sides (4 total). Cover and let sit for 30 minutes. Repeat this process every 30 minutes for 2 hours (for a total of 5 stretch and fold sessions).

Turn dough out onto a lightly floured surface and pre shape, cover with a tea towel and let rest for 20 minutes. Shape into a oval or ball and let it proof in a lined banneton basket overnight in the fridge.

Preheat bread pan or Dutch oven at 475° for 1 hour. Remove dough from the fridge and score immediately. Bake at 475° covered for 20 minutes, then uncovered for an additional 12-15 minutes until golden brown. Let cool on a wire rack for at least an hour before slicing.

Classic Mashed Potatoes 🥔 I’ve learned some important things over the years when it comes to almost everyone’s favorite Thanksgiving side:

1. The potato matters. Really fresh, organic, creamy Yukon gold potatoes are the best (I splurge and get mine at Whole Foods).
2. Salt the water REALLY REALLY well. It’s the only way to really flavor the potato. You’ll add more salt at the end but it won’t make up for under-salting during the cooking process. 
3. Don’t beat the bejeezus out of them unless you want a sticky gummy mess. I mash them by hand with a potato masher because I don’t mind a few chunks (which are only a problem if the potatoes are undercooked).
4. Simple is better, especially for the Thanksgiving meal. Put down the garlic and the cream cheese and let the potato shine (see point 1 above).

Directions:

Peel 3 pounds of Yukon gold potatoes and cut them into 1 inch cubes. Put them in a large pot and cover with cold water. Add a tablespoon of kosher salt and bring to a boil on the stove. Stir the potatoes occasionally so they don’t boil over for about 10-15 minutes or until you can pierce them easily with a fork. Drain in a colander and return to the pot. Add 4 tablespoons of good salted butter, 1/2 cup of heavy cream, and 1 teaspoon of kosher salt. Mash them gently by hand with a traditional potato masher until they get to the consistency you like. Add more salt and/or butter to taste. Serve warm with a few more tabs of butter on top, because a melted pool of butter is probably the prettiest thing ever.

Ingredients for casserole:
24 oz haricot verts (or regular green beans)
1 tbsp olive oil
3 tbsp butter
1 large shallot, minced
8 oz cremini mushrooms, sliced
5 oz shiitake mushrooms, sliced
3 cloves garlic, minced
2 tbsp flour
1 1/2 cups chicken stock
1 1/2 cups half and half
1/4 tsp nutmeg
1/2 cup Parmesan cheese, grated
Salt and pepper to taste

Preheat oven to 400. Blanch the beans in salted boiling water for 3 minutes, then submerge them in an ice bath, drain, and set aside. Heat oil and butter in a large cast iron skillet over medium high heat. Cook shallot until soft, then add mushrooms and cook until golden brown (don’t stir them too much so you get some crispy edges). Add garlic and a bit of salt and pepper to taste and cook for another couple minutes. Sprinkle flour on top of the mushrooms, stir well to coat, and cook for 2 more minutes. Slowly pour in the chicken both and bring to a boil, then turn down to a simmer, stirring often, until thick. Add half and half and nutmeg and cook for another 5 minutes, then stir in the Parmesan. Salt and pepper to taste. Stir in the green beans and sprinkle fried onions on top. Bake for about 20 minutes until the sides of the casserole are bubbling and the onions are a rich golden brown.

Ingredients for fried onions
1 sweet onion, sliced thinly
1 cup buttermilk
2 cups flour
1 tsp kosher salt, plus more for finishing
1/2 tsp black pepper
1/4 tsp cayenne
Vegetable oil for frying

Coat the onion slices in buttermilk. Heat the oil in a large stock pot to around 375. Mix flour, salt, pepper, and cayenne in a shallow bowl. Dredge onions in flour mixture and fry for 4-5 minutes until golden brown. Cool on a paper towel and salt immediately. Arrange on top of casserole.

Thanksgiving is tomorrow and these cheesy sourdough turkeys are the perfect festive snack! 🦃 I top these flaky biscuit crackers with Parmesan cheese and then serve them with homemade cranberry sauce spooned over a bit of cream cheese.

Note: This sourdough discard dough recipe is one of my greatest inventions - it’s a cross between buttery pie crust and flaky puff pastry. But if you don’t have sourdough starter you can substitute regular pie dough or puff pastry and this will still work beautifully!

Ingredients
3/4 cup flour
1/2 tsp sugar
1/2 tsp kosher salt
1/2 cup butter
1/2 cup unfed cold sourdough starter
1 egg, beaten
1/4 cup Parmesan cheese
Flake salt

Directions
Mix together flour, salt, and sugar in a food processor. Add cubes of butter and pulse until combined (you still want to see pea-sized pieces of butter in there). Scoop the sourdough starter on top and pulse until the dough begins to come together. Form dough into a disc and refrigerate for about an hour.

Preheat oven to 400°. Roll out dough to about 1/4 inch thick. Use a seasonal cookie cutter of your choice to make shaped crackers or just cut into squares. Brush with beaten egg and sprinkle with cheese and flake salt. Transfer crackers to a parchment lined baking sheet and bake for 15-20 minutes until golden brown.

Ingredients
2 sheets puff pastry
1/3 cup Nutella
1/4 cup sliced almonds

These sugared cranberries are as easy to make as they are beautiful. Use them for desserts, on cheeseboards, or alongside a festive holiday cocktail!

Ingredients
1 cup white sugar, divided
1/2 cup water
2 cups fresh cranberries

Directions
Make a simple syrup by combining 1/2 cup sugar and 1/2 cup water on a sauce pan over high heat. Bring to a boil to let sugar dissolve. Turn off heat and stir in the cranberries. Store covered at room temp for up to 4 days.

#Ad A fast, easy, and nutritious favorite - Mini Pumpkin Oat Muffins using @Quaker Old-Fashioned Oats!

Quaker Oats has been a trusted brand since 1877 and have been enjoyed by families, including my own, for generations! My mom used to make these for my brother and me when we were kids and it’s so fun to be able to pass on a classic family recipe using the same quality ingredients she did. And as a mom myself now, I love that Quaker Oats are carefully selected for quality, nutrition, and flavor.

We like to grab a couple of these little muffins to eat in the morning with some fruit and yogurt or pack them in lunchboxes to take to school.

Mini Pumpkin Oat Muffins

2 cups Quaker rolled oats
1 cup pumpkin puree
2 eggs
1 cup milk
1 ½ tbsp honey or pure maple syrup
2 tsp vanilla extract
1 tsp cinnamon
½ tsp ground cloves
½ tsp ground nutmeg
1 tsp baking soda
½ tsp baking powder
½ tsp kosher salt
Chocolate chips for topping (optional)
 
Preheat the oven to 375 degrees F and grease a mini muffin tin. Add all ingredients (minus the chocolate chips) to a food processor and pulse until smooth. Pour batter into the mini muffin tin and top each muffin with a few chocolate chips. Bake for 12-14 minutes until a tester inserted in the center of the muffin comes out clean. Let cool for 5 minutes and enjoy!
Note: Recipe makes 36 mini muffins. You can also use a regular muffin tin and increase the bake time by 5-8 minutes. Muffins store in the fridge for up to 5 days or in the freezer for up to 3 months.

Kahlúa baked Brie with pecans 🤎 This is one of my mom’s famous recipes and we insist that she makes it for just about every gathering. It’s insanely delicious and comes together so quickly!

Ingredients
1 whole 8oz -12oz round of Brie
1/2 cup Kahlúa liqueur
1/2 cup packed light brown sugar
1/2 cup pecans (we use a mixture of chopped and halved)
Baguette, crackers, green apple for serving

Preheat oven to 350°. Slice the top of the rind off the Brie (it helps if the cheese is very cold) and place in a covered baking dish (if you don’t have one of these just use a regular baking dish, replace the cut rind on top so the cheese doesn’t dry out in the oven, and discard the top when you take the Brie out of the oven). Bake for 15-20 minutes or until the Brie is melted and creamy.

In the meantime, combine Kahlua and sugar in a small saucepan and bring to a boil. Cook over low heat, stirring often, for about 10-15 minutes or until it reaches a caramel consistency. Remove from the heat and stir in the pecans. Spoon over the warm Brie and serve with sliced baguette, crackers, or Granny Smith apple slices.

Looking for an absolute showstopper this holiday season?? Make one of these donut hole Christmas trees! 🎄

Sourdough gingerbread biscuits 🤎 These flaky little shortbread-style biscuits are my new favorite invention. The gingerbread flavor is subtle and they’re not super sweet, making them just as at home on a cheeseboard as they are on a cookie plate.

Ingredients
3/4 cup AP flour
1/4 cup brown sugar
2 tsp gingerbread spice
1/2 tsp kosher salt
1 stick (8 tbsp) very cold unsalted butter, cut into small cubes
1/2 cup sourdough starter discard
Turbinado sugar for sprinkling 

Directions
Combine flour, sugar, gingerbread spice, and salt in a food processor and pulse to combine. Add butter and pulse until the butter is broken down to about the size of peas. Add sourdough starter (better if it’s cold from the fridge!) and pulse until a crumbly dough forms. Press into a disk and refrigerate for at least an hour.

Preheat oven to 400°. Roll out the dough and cut into gingerbread shapes. Arrange on a parchment lined cookie sheet, sprinkle with Turbinado sugar, and bake for 12-15 minutes until golden brown.

Eggnog Pound Cake 🤎 Rich and buttery, with all your favorite festive flavors... this delectable dessert is perfect for the whole holiday season! It’s delicious after a meal with family and friends (especially paired with a glass of bourbon) and equally perfect the next morning with a hot cup of coffee.

Ingredients
1½ cups butter, room temp
2 cups white sugar
1 teaspoon salt
4 large eggs, room temp
3 cups cake flour
1 cup eggnog
1 tbsp bourbon
1 tbsp vanilla extract
1 tsp freshly grated nutmeg
2 tsp cinnamon

Preheat oven to 325 degrees and spray a 12 cup bundt pan with non-stick baking spray. Cream together butter, sugar, and salt on high speed until light and fluffy (about 5 minutes). Add eggs one at a time, mixing well. Next add the flour slowly on low speed. Now for all the flavor! Mix in the eggnog, bourbon, vanilla extract, nutmeg, and cinnamon until combined. Pour batter into bundt pan and bake for about 70-80 minutes or until a toothpick comes out mostly clean. Let cool for about 15 minutes, then gently release from the pan and let it cool completely. Dust with powdered sugar and enjoy!

A one-skillet meal that has it all - crispy chicken, spicy sausage, creamy sauce, and even a good amount of leafy greens to balance it all out.

Ingredients
1 lb hot Italian sausage
4 bone-in skin-on chicken thighs
1 shallot, chopped
2 cloves garlic, minced
1/2 cup dry white wine
1 cup chicken stock
3-4 cups kale
15.5 oz cannellini beans, drained and rinsed
4 oz cream cheese

Directions
Preheat oven to 400. Heat a bit of olive oil in a cast iron skillet over medium high heat. Brown the sausage, crumbling as it cooks. Remove sausage from the pan. Add more oil if necessary, then brown the chicken thighs skin side down for 4 min, then flip and cook another 4 minutes. Remove the chicken and set aside. Cook the shallot in the same pan for a few minutes, then throw in the garlic and sauté until fragrant. Deglaze with white wine and scrape up and brown bits. Let it reduce by about half. Add chicken stock and bring to a boil. Throw the cooked sausage back in the pan and add kale, cooking until wilted. Stir in the beans. Add salt and pepper to taste. Nestle the chicken back in the pan skin-side up and throw the whole thing in the oven for 25-30 minutes or until the chicken is crispy and cooked through. To finish the sauce, remove the chicken and set aside. Stir in cream cheese and season with salt and pepper to taste. Lay the chicken back on top and serve straight out of the skillet with some sourdough bread.

Nutella & strawberry braid 🍓🤎 This simple dessert could not be easier or more delicious, and you only need a few ingredients and less than 30 minutes start to finish. It’s perfect if you want to make a quick homemade treat for your valentine!

Ingredients
1 sheet puff pastry, thawed
1/2 cup Nutella
1 cup strawberries, sliced
1 egg, beaten
1 tbsp Turbinado sugar

Preheat oven to 400°. Roll out puff pastry a bit, then spread Nutella on the middle third section. Arrange sliced strawberries on top. Slide the puff pastry in either side into 1/2 inch strip and fold over the strawberries and Nutella. Brush pastry with egg wash and sprinkle with Turbinado sugar. Bake on a parchment lined sheet pan for 15-20 min or until pastry is golden brown. Let cool slightly, then drizzle with a bit more melted Nutella (and arrange heart shaped strawberries on top if you want to be extra festive for Valentine’s Day ❤️).

Buffalo chicken stuffed avocados 🥑 A delicious and nutrient-dense snack for game day! The spicy Buffalo chicken and creamy avocado is the yummiest combination, and the avocado halves make perfect little bowls so everyone can grab their own portion! Serve with tortilla chips for scooping and you’ve got the perfect football snack.

Ingredients
1 lb chicken breast
½ cup Frank’s Red Hot Sauce
¼ cup butter
1 tsp garlic powder
3 avocados, halved and pits removed
Green onion, chopped
Blue cheese crumbles
Tortilla chips for serving

Directions
Add chicken, hot sauce, butter, and garlic powder to a slow cooker and cook on high for 4 hours, then shred. Scoop out a bit of avocado from each half and fill with shredded chicken. Top with green onion, blue cheese crumbles, and a couple dashes of hot sauce. Serve with tortilla chips.

Sweet and Salty Chex Mix 💞 The perfect snack for this time of the year! And super easy to make when you have kiddos “helping” you in the kitchen. 👍

Ingredients
1 cup white chocolate chips (@ghirardelli is the best)
1/2 cup creamy peanut butter
4 tbsp salted butter
3 cups of rice @chexcereal
3 cups corn @chexcereal
3 cups of pretzels (I use the XO ones from @utzsnacks)
1 cup powdered sugar
2 cups peanut @mmschocolate

Combine white chocolate chips, peanut butter, and butter in a glass bowl. Microwave until melted (about 2 minutes) and stir until very smooth. In a separate large bowl, combine Chex and pretzels. Pour the chocolate mixture over top and stir until coated. Throw it all in a large ziplock bag with powdered sugar and shake until coated. Spread the snack mix out on a couple sheets of wax paper to cool for about 10 minutes, then mix in m&m’s (I used peanut m&m’s this time but you can use whatever you prefer!). Try not to eat it all at once.

Flank steak tacos with pickled red onion and avocado 🌮 I love a slow cooker meal in the winter and this one couldn’t be easier or more delicious!

Ingredients
2lbs flank steak
1 yellow onion, chopped
4 cloves garlic
4oz green chilis
2 tbsp taco seasoning
17oz beef bone broth
Pickled red onions (ingredients below)
Tortillas
Avocado, sliced

Ingredients for pickled red onion
1 red onion, thinly sliced
1/2 cup water
1/4 cup apple cider vinegar
1/4 cup white vinegar
1 tsp sea salt
2 tsp honey

Combine steak, yellow onion, garlic, green chilis, taco seasoning, and broth in a slow cooker and cook on high for 6 hours. In the meantime, combine ingredients for pickled red onions in a glass jar and put in the fridge until ready to serve (give it at least an hour).

When the steak is finished, shred with a fork and serve on tortillas with pickled onions and avocado.
